>>Assume you have the following problem: given two sentences, decide if the first one is a translation of the second one. Which setup would you try? <<

( ) Generative with a word-based vocabulary. {{Even if this may seem a pure translation task, the real goal is to classify the relationship between two sentences.}}
( ) Generative classification with a subword-based vocabulary. {{Even if this may seem a pure translation task, the real goal is to classify the relationship between two sentences.}}
( ) Generative classification with a character-based vocabulary. {{Even if this may seem a pure translation task, the real goal is to classify the relationship between two sentences.}}
(x) Sentence pair-level classification with a subword-based vocabulary. {{Correct! Since the output is a yes or no answer, this is a classification task. Using subwords leverages the compositionality principle to find smaller pieces that are meaningful in both languages.}}
( ) Sentence pair-level classification with a word-based vocabulary. {{Sentence pair-level classification is the correct approach. Moreover, given we have two languages in the sentence, a subword approach should be better in decomposing words into smaller pieces that are meaningful in both languages.}}
